{{Politics of Samoa}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Samoa]] on 12 November 1990. Voters were asked whether they approved of the introduction of [[universal suffrage]] and a second chamber of Parliament. The first change was approved by 52.6% of voters, but the second opposed by 60.7%. Voter turnout was 74.3% for the first question and 73.7% for the second.<ref>Nohlen, D, Grotz, F & Hartmann, C (2001) ''Elections in Asia: A data handbook, Volume II'', p786 {{ISBN|0-19-924959-8}}</ref>
Although universal suffrage was introduced, candidates in elections still had to be part of the [[Fa'amatai|Matai]].<ref>Nohlen, D, Grotz, F & Hartmann, C (2001) ''Elections in Asia: A data handbook, Volume II'', p54 {{ISBN|0-19-924959-8}}</ref>
